WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.340 --> 00:00:07.160
AACR ongoing commitment to the growth and support of

2
00:00:07.200 --> 00:00:11.140
pathologists who are engaged in cancer research worldwide.

3
00:00:11.860 --> 00:00:15.660
This year, we are honored to present this distinguished award

4
00:00:16.020 --> 00:00:19.560
to Dr. David Rim, the Anthony N.

5
00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:23.160
Brady Professor of Pathology and Professor of Medicine,

6
00:00:23.620 --> 00:00:27.540
Director of Yale Cancer Center Tissue Microarray Facility, and the

7
00:00:27.620 --> 00:00:30.100
Director of Yale Pathology Tissue Service

8
00:00:30.920 --> 00:00:34.620
at Yale School of Medicine. Dr. Rim is an

9
00:00:34.700 --> 00:00:37.840
exceptional scientist and pathologist whose

10
00:00:37.880 --> 00:00:41.700
innovations in quantitative biomarker science have

11
00:00:41.740 --> 00:00:45.360
transformed cancer diagnosis and informed modern

12
00:00:45.420 --> 00:00:47.480
approaches to precision medicine.

13
00:00:48.340 --> 00:00:51.940
His work has pushed the boundaries of how we

14
00:00:51.980 --> 00:00:55.460
measure, interpret, and clinically apply

15
00:00:55.860 --> 00:00:57.980
biomarkers in human tissue.

16
00:00:59.200 --> 00:01:03.180
A central focus of Dr. Rim's career has been

17
00:01:03.190 --> 00:01:07.000
the development of rigorous quantitative methods for

18
00:01:07.040 --> 00:01:10.920
tissue biomarker research. In early studies of

19
00:01:10.960 --> 00:01:14.880
prognostic biomarkers in breast cancer, he identified

20
00:01:14.920 --> 00:01:18.130
a challenge, the lack of accurate and

21
00:01:18.200 --> 00:01:22.120
reproducible tools to quantify predictive

22
00:01:22.220 --> 00:01:25.940
biomarkers in tissue specimens. To address this,

23
00:01:26.120 --> 00:01:30.020
he invented the EquAsystem in 2002,

24
00:01:30.420 --> 00:01:34.260
a groundbreaking fluorescent-based platform

25
00:01:34.360 --> 00:01:36.720
for automated quantitative analysis.

26
00:01:37.720 --> 00:01:41.500
This innovation revolutionized immunohistochemistry,

27
00:01:42.240 --> 00:01:45.860
establishing a new benchmark for precision,

28
00:01:46.600 --> 00:01:50.170
and enabling the widespread adoption of quantitative

29
00:01:50.240 --> 00:01:50.920
pathology.

30
00:01:51.860 --> 00:01:55.780
Building on this work, Dr. Rim became an early

31
00:01:55.880 --> 00:01:59.380
leader in the use of tissue microarray, and his

32
00:01:59.440 --> 00:02:02.080
laboratory developed imaging

33
00:02:02.880 --> 00:02:06.580
pipelines for hotspot identification and quantitative

34
00:02:06.660 --> 00:02:07.320
analysis.

35
00:02:08.670 --> 00:02:12.440
These advances enabled essential studies into biomarker

36
00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:15.920
heterogeneity, including the clinical significance of

37
00:02:15.980 --> 00:02:19.800
EGFR and estrogen receptor variability in breast

38
00:02:19.840 --> 00:02:20.269
cancer.

39
00:02:21.240 --> 00:02:24.720
More recently, Dr. Rim has applied his biomarker

40
00:02:25.200 --> 00:02:27.500
expertise to cancer immunotherapy.

41
00:02:28.220 --> 00:02:28.580
His

42
00:02:29.540 --> 00:02:32.840
investigations into the prognostic and predictive role of

43
00:02:32.920 --> 00:02:36.460
PD-L1 expression across breast cancer,

44
00:02:37.060 --> 00:02:40.480
melanoma, and lung cancer demonstrated that

45
00:02:40.520 --> 00:02:44.000
PD-L1 alone is insufficient as a biomarker

46
00:02:44.380 --> 00:02:48.100
unless evaluated in the context of specific immune cell

47
00:02:48.180 --> 00:02:52.000
subsets and their spatial relationship to tumor

48
00:02:52.040 --> 00:02:55.640
cells. This insight has shaped modern approaches to

49
00:02:55.680 --> 00:02:57.840
immunotherapy biomarker assessment.

50
00:02:59.080 --> 00:03:01.700
Dr. Rim's contribution to biomarker science

51
00:03:02.180 --> 00:03:06.060
have had a profound impact. He

52
00:03:06.080 --> 00:03:09.760
has played a central role in national and international efforts

53
00:03:10.160 --> 00:03:13.600
to establish guidelines for biomarker evaluation,

54
00:03:13.760 --> 00:03:17.520
particularly for HER2, ER, and PR in

55
00:03:17.600 --> 00:03:20.930
breast cancer, directly improving diagnostic

56
00:03:21.100 --> 00:03:23.800
accuracy and patient care worldwide.

57
00:03:24.620 --> 00:03:28.600
Dr. Rim has been a dedicated AACR member

58
00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:30.860
since 2002, and his leadership,

59
00:03:31.820 --> 00:03:35.120
scholarship, and innovation have left an

60
00:03:35.280 --> 00:03:38.760
indelible mark in the field of pathology and on cancer

61
00:03:38.840 --> 00:03:40.220
research as a whole.

62
00:03:41.040 --> 00:03:44.640
It is my great honor to introduce the

63
00:03:44.660 --> 00:03:48.260
2026 recipient of the AACR

64
00:03:48.760 --> 00:03:52.630
James S. Ewing–Thelma B. Dunn Award for

65
00:03:52.780 --> 00:03:56.680
Outstanding Achievement in Pathology in Cancer Research,

66
00:03:57.100 --> 00:03:58.080
Dr. David Rim.

67
00:04:04.120 --> 00:04:07.220
Thanks, Dr. Kapoor, for that very flattering introduction.

68
00:04:07.700 --> 00:04:10.680
I have a lot to live up to now. And thanks also for

69
00:04:11.380 --> 00:04:14.620
the committee for selecting me. I had to read the email multiple times.

70
00:04:14.640 --> 00:04:18.180
I was so surprised that I was actually the selection this year.

71
00:04:18.860 --> 00:04:22.220
What I want to do, though, is nicely summarized in your introduction, that is, talk

72
00:04:22.300 --> 00:04:23.070
about

73
00:04:24.360 --> 00:04:27.740
the underlying concept of how we

74
00:04:27.780 --> 00:04:30.520
quantify pathology and how we make it reproducible,

75
00:04:31.500 --> 00:04:34.340
as opposed to what we

76
00:04:36.040 --> 00:04:39.900
mostly have in pathology today. I want to just show my disclosures first

77
00:04:39.940 --> 00:04:43.760
and note that a lot of the work that I do is sponsored by biotech or

78
00:04:43.840 --> 00:04:45.640
pharma because we have mutual interests.

79
00:04:46.340 --> 00:04:48.700
Although some of it is sponsored by NCI as well.

80
00:04:49.660 --> 00:04:53.640
Today, in the next 30 minutes or so, I want to talk about Dr. Ewing and Dr.

81
00:04:53.880 --> 00:04:56.850
Dunn and their contribution to anatomic pathology just briefly.

82
00:04:57.380 --> 00:05:00.540
But then I want to talk about spatial analysis of histology, because that's the

83
00:05:00.580 --> 00:05:02.070
heart of what pathology really is.

84
00:05:02.750 --> 00:05:03.280
And then

85
00:05:04.220 --> 00:05:07.560
talk about measuring and what we've done, what we've contributed to the field in

86
00:05:07.640 --> 00:05:11.240
measurement, and what we've done more recently in terms of

87
00:05:11.280 --> 00:05:15.080
bringing standardization to measurement, which I think is something I should have

88
00:05:15.120 --> 00:05:18.900
thought of 20 years ago, but here we are today just now standardizing it.

89
00:05:18.920 --> 00:05:21.840
Then finally, I'll talk about the newest concept we're working on in my lab, and

90
00:05:21.860 --> 00:05:22.500
the idea that

91
00:05:23.940 --> 00:05:27.760
there needs to be a biomarker that selects between drugs.

92
00:05:27.820 --> 00:05:31.720
Not just a companion diagnostic for a single drug, but a biomarker that

93
00:05:31.740 --> 00:05:35.620
selects between drugs that are both eligible for treating a patient in the

94
00:05:35.680 --> 00:05:37.560
same clinical setting.

95
00:05:39.080 --> 00:05:40.600
So, this is Dr. Ewing.

96
00:05:41.640 --> 00:05:44.760
He graduated in 1897 and was the first

97
00:05:45.220 --> 00:05:48.080
professor of clinical pathology at Medical

98
00:05:48.980 --> 00:05:52.960
College of Cornell University, and he was one of the founding members

99
00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:56.900
of AACR back in 1907. And I think that

100
00:05:57.680 --> 00:05:58.240
probably what

101
00:05:59.320 --> 00:06:03.172
has led to hison the named award. The

102
00:06:03.232 --> 00:06:06.592
other perhaps most significant contribution is the Ewing sarcoma.

103
00:06:07.072 --> 00:06:10.672
It was originally called the diffuse endothelioma of bone,

104
00:06:11.432 --> 00:06:15.052
and published, but now known as Ewing sarcoma, which we all learn in our first or

105
00:06:15.112 --> 00:06:16.732
second year of pathology residency.

106
00:06:17.212 --> 00:06:20.051
And it's a tough one, but we'll get back to that in a minute.

107
00:06:20.532 --> 00:06:23.842
And then he was featured on the cover of Time magazine, perhaps the only

108
00:06:23.852 --> 00:06:26.102
pathologist ever to be on the cover of Time magazine,

109
00:06:27.652 --> 00:06:30.732
and then ultimately retired in 1939.

110
00:06:30.752 --> 00:06:33.952
But the award is not just named for Dr. Ewing, it's also named for Dr. Dunn.

111
00:06:34.692 --> 00:06:38.332
Dr. Dunn had an interesting career as well.

112
00:06:39.512 --> 00:06:43.012
She got her MD in 1926 before women got

113
00:06:43.152 --> 00:06:46.272
MDs. She was one of the only women in her class to get an MD.

114
00:06:46.832 --> 00:06:50.772
Ultimately, became an assistant professor at UVA, but then a

115
00:06:50.832 --> 00:06:53.352
year later, married William Dunn and took his last name.

116
00:06:54.152 --> 00:06:58.092
And so this award is named the Ewing Thelma Brumfield Dunn

117
00:06:58.152 --> 00:06:58.552
Award.

118
00:06:59.852 --> 00:07:03.502
And then the most interesting part, perhaps, of her career is what doesn't

119
00:07:03.592 --> 00:07:07.432
happen now. That is, she moved to Washington and took a six-year hiatus to

120
00:07:07.452 --> 00:07:11.442
raise three children. I'm proud to say that probably half of my graduate

121
00:07:11.472 --> 00:07:14.952
students have had children while they're in the lab completing their thesis.

122
00:07:15.392 --> 00:07:16.132
That's how it should be.

123
00:07:16.992 --> 00:07:19.132
We shouldn't have to see a hiatus in

124
00:07:19.992 --> 00:07:22.152
careers in order for women to

125
00:07:23.372 --> 00:07:23.872
excel.

126
00:07:25.252 --> 00:07:28.552
In the end, she was a clinical instructor, ultimately led a fellow at the

127
00:07:28.612 --> 00:07:32.442
NCI, where she led a lot of laboratory mouse work,

128
00:07:32.492 --> 00:07:36.312
and in fact, that was her claim to fame was to sort of really opening up the

129
00:07:36.352 --> 00:07:39.422
field of using mouse models in research.

130
00:07:40.452 --> 00:07:44.182
And then she was a staff pathologist, published classifications of tumors,

131
00:07:44.612 --> 00:07:48.172
and ultimately the first woman president of AACR, which has landed her

132
00:07:48.272 --> 00:07:52.172
as a name on this award, which I'm very proud to

133
00:07:52.212 --> 00:07:53.232
have received.

134
00:07:54.912 --> 00:07:58.092
So what about spatial analysis? Let's move on to that next.

135
00:07:58.172 --> 00:08:01.512
Spatial analysis is the basis of anatomic pathology, and I like to use this

136
00:08:01.572 --> 00:08:05.412
illustration. This is all the information of color

137
00:08:05.872 --> 00:08:09.642
in a Monet and a Renoir, but the only thing that's missing is the spatial

138
00:08:09.692 --> 00:08:13.552
information. So here is the intensity scale, and then this is the blue, the

139
00:08:13.572 --> 00:08:17.052
green, and the red that make up these two masterpieces.

140
00:08:17.612 --> 00:08:19.672
Does anyone want to speculate on which is which?

141
00:08:21.212 --> 00:08:24.752
So sometimes there's an art history major in the audience that says, "Oh, a lot of

142
00:08:24.792 --> 00:08:27.252
light blue. This one must be the Monet." And they're right.

143
00:08:27.872 --> 00:08:31.042
But I've yet to have an audience that can tell me this is "The Boating Party" and

144
00:08:31.052 --> 00:08:34.492
this is "The Stroll." And that's because of the two-dimensional information.

145
00:08:34.533 --> 00:08:37.072
And that's why what we do as pathologists is so important.

146
00:08:37.112 --> 00:08:40.812
In fact, it's integration of that two-dimensional information into a final

147
00:08:40.832 --> 00:08:44.432
diagnosis and into patterns and into classifications

148
00:08:44.832 --> 00:08:46.592
that really is what pathology's all about.

149
00:08:47.692 --> 00:08:51.632
The rest of the world finally recognized that in 2024 when spatial proteomics

150
00:08:51.652 --> 00:08:54.651
or spatial biology was declared the method of the year.

151
00:08:54.672 --> 00:08:55.802
But it's funny that it took

152
00:08:56.672 --> 00:09:00.632
2024 before it was called the method of the year, because we've been

153
00:09:00.652 --> 00:09:04.572
doing spatial analysis since Ewing and even before then,

154
00:09:05.852 --> 00:09:07.632
when we looked at two-dimensional

155
00:09:08.472 --> 00:09:12.032
tissue slides. And here it is. So here's the spatial analysis of the Ewing

156
00:09:12.092 --> 00:09:14.312
sarcoma. And you can see this is a hard one.

157
00:09:14.352 --> 00:09:18.272
There's not a lot of distinguishing features to compare to some spatial analysis of

158
00:09:18.312 --> 00:09:21.792
some tumor types. But you can see this list of bullet points of

159
00:09:21.852 --> 00:09:25.692
how we, as pathologists, try to define Ewing sarcoma, and now more

160
00:09:25.752 --> 00:09:29.372
recently, how we can define it from a molecular alteration.

161
00:09:29.412 --> 00:09:32.772
And this is important, too, because I think that what we're seeing now is the

162
00:09:32.832 --> 00:09:36.592
evolution from spatial information to spatial plus molecular

163
00:09:36.652 --> 00:09:38.782
information, and I think that that's what--

164
00:09:39.872 --> 00:09:43.561
And by far, the most contribution for spatial information

165
00:09:44.312 --> 00:09:47.692
or molecular information has been from genomic work, DNA

166
00:09:48.192 --> 00:09:51.392
assessment. But I would argue that protein is equally important.

167
00:09:51.472 --> 00:09:53.192
Actually, protein is closer to function.

168
00:09:53.692 --> 00:09:57.292
And so we've focused, in my career, on measuring protein.

169
00:09:58.372 --> 00:09:59.152
Speaking of measuring,

170
00:10:00.112 --> 00:10:03.372
I like to define two different terms as we start out.

171
00:10:03.452 --> 00:10:06.792
Reading is what pathologists do. It's the subjective but expert

172
00:10:06.812 --> 00:10:09.332
interpretation of information on the histology slide.

173
00:10:09.962 --> 00:10:13.322
Whereas measuring is a quantitative, objective determination of amounts or

174
00:10:13.392 --> 00:10:17.072
concentrations of protein or signal on a histopathology slide.

175
00:10:17.572 --> 00:10:21.311
And it's sort of been my mission over my career to move from reading to measuring.

176
00:10:23.592 --> 00:10:26.792
So can we do it without any special molecular tools?

177
00:10:27.152 --> 00:10:30.972
Well, yes. Now with all the AI and image analysis

178
00:10:31.032 --> 00:10:33.172
tools, we can actually start to measure.

179
00:10:34.112 --> 00:10:36.972
And this is an example of segmentation measuring lymphocytes.

180
00:10:37.952 --> 00:10:39.412
Let's see if that's going to work or not.

181
00:10:41.322 --> 00:10:44.722
Measuring lymphocytes and tumor cells by spatial information and

182
00:10:44.812 --> 00:10:45.852
segmentation alone.

183
00:10:46.832 --> 00:10:49.092
However, it doesn't always work so well. Look at this one.

184
00:10:49.672 --> 00:10:53.552
Here, half of the cells that are lymphocytes are considered to be tumor cells,

185
00:10:54.052 --> 00:10:57.632
and probably vice versa. So measurement still has a little ways to go.

186
00:10:57.712 --> 00:11:01.562
Now, this is a pretty primitive segmentation tool, and it's getting better and

187
00:11:01.632 --> 00:11:05.172
better, as you can see that a multi-pass segmentation

188
00:11:05.572 --> 00:11:05.872
tool

189
00:11:06.872 --> 00:11:10.832
from Janice Taub and Alex Salehi has improved cell segmentation dramatically.

190
00:11:10.862 --> 00:11:14.592
And then there are other software algorithms that have improved

191
00:11:14.632 --> 00:11:18.332
segmentation by using not just cells, but other entities.

192
00:11:18.852 --> 00:11:22.152
But finally, I would argue that it's still a challenge to segment things that are

193
00:11:22.212 --> 00:11:24.852
not easily segmented, like this. So if you

194
00:11:25.692 --> 00:11:29.662
imagine taking a section through here, you wouldn't just see round items with

195
00:11:29.692 --> 00:11:33.492
a nucleus. You'd see little sections of lymphocyte, and if you hit this

196
00:11:33.532 --> 00:11:36.192
one toward the North Pole, you might not see a nucleus.

197
00:11:36.572 --> 00:11:40.492
And so those represent some of the challenges of segmentation that are now actually

198
00:11:40.552 --> 00:11:42.192
being addressed pretty well

199
00:11:43.392 --> 00:11:43.622
by

200
00:11:46.092 --> 00:11:50.072
AI. This is just to show another example of a hard-to-segment case, and

201
00:11:50.132 --> 00:11:51.812
time will tell if we can segment this,

202
00:11:52.932 --> 00:11:53.472
where you have a

203
00:11:54.892 --> 00:11:58.292
single tentacle of a cell or a dendrite reaching down into other

204
00:11:58.332 --> 00:12:02.232
epithelial cells.And this is what we've done so far, and this is actually a

205
00:12:02.252 --> 00:12:06.032
poster that's being shown right now where we try to calculate

206
00:12:06.112 --> 00:12:09.662
something quantitative, in this case TILS or tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes,

207
00:12:10.062 --> 00:12:13.992
and take an image that's not been molecularly treated in any way other

208
00:12:14.032 --> 00:12:17.912
than the H&amp;E, hematoxylin and eosin, and make a quantitative result

209
00:12:17.932 --> 00:12:21.072
out of it. Now, we're just scratching the surface in my lab.

210
00:12:21.112 --> 00:12:25.092
This is work that we did in collaboration with Anat Matoubushi, looking at all the

211
00:12:25.112 --> 00:12:26.892
different ways you can quantify the H&amp;E.

212
00:12:27.312 --> 00:12:31.132
And in fact, the number and mechanisms of ways of quantification of the

213
00:12:31.172 --> 00:12:34.992
H&amp;E using artificial intelligence and image analysis

214
00:12:35.052 --> 00:12:38.852
are shocking. And one wonders as the session

215
00:12:38.892 --> 00:12:42.292
before that I attended before this one was

216
00:12:42.512 --> 00:12:45.952
determining the expression profile and transcriptomics based on the

217
00:12:46.092 --> 00:12:49.412
H&amp;E. Can they really do that? Well, time will tell, but there's a lot of people

218
00:12:49.422 --> 00:12:53.152
talking at this very meeting about looking at being able to determine which

219
00:12:53.252 --> 00:12:56.012
RNAs are expressed from the H&amp;E alone.

220
00:12:56.652 --> 00:12:59.052
Time will tell, but it's certainly more quantitative than

221
00:13:00.832 --> 00:13:03.012
just looking at it and giving a subjective read.

222
00:13:04.572 --> 00:13:07.602
So let's talk about measuring, because what we can measure and what

223
00:13:09.172 --> 00:13:11.532
I've spent my career doing is trying to measure protein.

224
00:13:13.052 --> 00:13:16.932
So this is where it all started. This guy is Clive Taylor, and the story goes that

225
00:13:16.992 --> 00:13:20.752
Clive-- and this is sort of the timeline of protein

226
00:13:20.792 --> 00:13:24.752
assessment. And in 1974, Clive Taylor took

227
00:13:24.812 --> 00:13:28.192
an immunofluorescent image of a tissue slide to

228
00:13:28.232 --> 00:13:31.832
his mentor, David Mason, and said, "So what do you think?"

229
00:13:32.312 --> 00:13:35.572
And David said, "This is great, but I can't see the tumor surrounding the

230
00:13:35.652 --> 00:13:36.992
interesting expression pattern.

231
00:13:37.392 --> 00:13:40.672
Can you do something about that?" And so he went back into the lab

232
00:13:41.232 --> 00:13:41.392
and

233
00:13:43.072 --> 00:13:46.932
generated a chromogenic method that is a way that blocked light so that you could

234
00:13:46.992 --> 00:13:48.412
counter-stain with hematoxylin.

235
00:13:48.932 --> 00:13:52.892
And that result gave images that look like this, where

236
00:13:52.932 --> 00:13:56.692
there's the H&amp;E, and then if it's positive for the protein that you're trying to

237
00:13:56.752 --> 00:14:00.692
assess, like p63 in the case of this squamous cell carcinoma, it's dark

238
00:14:00.712 --> 00:14:04.292
brown. And if it's negative, you don't see any brown at all.

239
00:14:04.762 --> 00:14:08.511
And so this is what the assay was designed for, was using it for a selective or

240
00:14:08.632 --> 00:14:12.152
diagnostic assay in order to figure out what the tumor's expressing.

241
00:14:12.232 --> 00:14:16.202
So in this case, if it's TTF1 positive, it's an adenocarcinoma, and

242
00:14:16.272 --> 00:14:18.752
p63 positive, it's a squamous cell carcinoma.

243
00:14:19.812 --> 00:14:20.402
And that

244
00:14:21.692 --> 00:14:24.512
binary choice of diagnosis is what

245
00:14:24.521 --> 00:14:28.352
the chromogenic method that Clive Taylor

246
00:14:28.372 --> 00:14:30.432
invented was really designed for.

247
00:14:30.452 --> 00:14:34.292
Since then, we've pushed the method to places that probably it shouldn't go,

248
00:14:34.692 --> 00:14:37.292
and that is making it quantitative or semi-quantitative.

249
00:14:37.752 --> 00:14:39.392
Semi-quantitative because of scores.

250
00:14:39.432 --> 00:14:42.552
And when I started as a resident, I was told immunohistochemistry would never be

251
00:14:42.592 --> 00:14:45.172
quantitative. It would only ever be semi-quantitative.

252
00:14:45.192 --> 00:14:48.432
And pretty much that's right with the tools that we use for standard

253
00:14:48.492 --> 00:14:52.472
immunohistochemistry. That is, chromogens have great limitations as a tool for

254
00:14:52.552 --> 00:14:53.092
measurement.

255
00:14:53.932 --> 00:14:57.842
And you can see that there's not only the problem of the intensity of

256
00:14:57.872 --> 00:15:01.652
the chromogen, but the intensity of the background hematoxylin.

257
00:15:02.052 --> 00:15:05.932
And all these variables make it difficult to measure an immunohistochemistry

258
00:15:05.992 --> 00:15:06.412
slide.

259
00:15:07.752 --> 00:15:10.012
To verify this, this is actually the fifth edition.

260
00:15:10.112 --> 00:15:12.232
The sixth edition is now out, but I got a kick out of this.

261
00:15:12.732 --> 00:15:16.412
There's 944 pages, nine of which are on quantitative information.

262
00:15:16.902 --> 00:15:20.842
And the sixth edition is no better or worse, that is, that

263
00:15:20.842 --> 00:15:24.752
quantitative aspects of immunohistochemistry are not considered to be that

264
00:15:24.812 --> 00:15:26.052
important for pathologists.

265
00:15:27.872 --> 00:15:31.812
But I want to focus on that. And this was a

266
00:15:31.852 --> 00:15:35.572
binary marker made for HER2 to give or not give trastuzumab,

267
00:15:35.752 --> 00:15:39.352
probably the most important drug in breast cancer in our generation.

268
00:15:39.372 --> 00:15:42.452
And if it looked like this, that was 3 plus, those were positive, and the rest of

269
00:15:42.472 --> 00:15:45.772
them were negative. And so if it looked like this, you did some other tricks.

270
00:15:45.892 --> 00:15:49.812
You did in situ hybridization to

271
00:15:49.852 --> 00:15:52.672
determine whether or not it was actually an amplified gene or not.

272
00:15:53.012 --> 00:15:55.852
But these are probably all gene amplified, and these are not.

273
00:15:56.192 --> 00:15:59.732
But now we're asked to tell the difference between zero and one.

274
00:16:00.192 --> 00:16:04.092
This is something that pathologists have no business doing, but we're asked to

275
00:16:04.132 --> 00:16:07.492
do that, in fact, required to do that in order to prescribe a

276
00:16:07.512 --> 00:16:11.292
drug. If the patient's going to get trastuzumab deruxtecan, they have to have at

277
00:16:11.332 --> 00:16:14.932
least a zero plus or originally a one plus, not a zero

278
00:16:15.332 --> 00:16:16.791
in order to get that. Can we do that?

279
00:16:17.532 --> 00:16:21.312
Well, here's the new task, and here's how we've done on it so far.

280
00:16:21.692 --> 00:16:25.672
This is work from Jack Robinson in our lab done a few years back, where

281
00:16:25.712 --> 00:16:29.692
we gave 18 different pathologists 170 cases and said, "Just score it according

282
00:16:29.712 --> 00:16:32.632
to the ASCO/CAP guidelines." We didn't tell them we were going to look at the

283
00:16:32.652 --> 00:16:36.332
difference between zero and one, but we told them, "Just score it according to the

284
00:16:36.392 --> 00:16:40.032
ASCO/CAP guidelines. Let's see how you do." And what you see is that pathologist

285
00:16:40.112 --> 00:16:43.552
number one, 44% of the patients were not qualified for

286
00:16:43.612 --> 00:16:47.542
trastuzumab deruxtecan, but on those same slides, pathologist number

287
00:16:47.612 --> 00:16:51.532
18 only disqualified 15%. So that means whether or not you

288
00:16:51.572 --> 00:16:55.212
got a drug depended on who your pathologist was, not the

289
00:16:55.252 --> 00:16:56.292
biology of your tumor.

290
00:16:57.832 --> 00:17:01.152
Was it just us? No. Since then, there's been a number of other studies.

291
00:17:01.192 --> 00:17:04.522
Here's a study in Japan with 144 pathologists reading 20 cases.

292
00:17:05.012 --> 00:17:08.133
Their overall agreement was 63%, a little better than we had.

293
00:17:08.992 --> 00:17:12.853
And then in Australia, nine pathologists did 60 cases with an

294
00:17:12.932 --> 00:17:16.873
overall agreement of 80%. And probably the best sort of

295
00:17:16.892 --> 00:17:20.572
ring study was done by Joe Rusoff and colleagues, actually 77

296
00:17:20.613 --> 00:17:22.412
pathologists, mostly from European countries.

297
00:17:22.972 --> 00:17:26.912
And what they found is that to agree on zero, they

298
00:17:26.952 --> 00:17:30.632
use the term overall rater agreement and not even using

299
00:17:30.652 --> 00:17:34.432
pathologists, raters, which is technically the right way to do a

300
00:17:34.452 --> 00:17:38.292
comparison study like this. And you can see that their overall rater agreement

301
00:17:38.332 --> 00:17:39.932
was 83% or 82%

302
00:17:40.852 --> 00:17:44.212
for 4b5, which is HER2 by the standard

303
00:17:44.292 --> 00:17:45.592
FDA-approved assay.

304
00:17:46.672 --> 00:17:50.382
Interestingly, they thought that maybe we could train this, and in fact, you

305
00:17:50.472 --> 00:17:53.762
can't train it. You can see no statistically significant increase with

306
00:17:53.812 --> 00:17:57.012
training pathologists on how to read HER2 low.

307
00:17:58.792 --> 00:18:01.732
Also interesting is we're really good at HER2 high.

308
00:18:01.792 --> 00:18:04.872
If it's HER2 amplified, we're going to get that right, and that's because that's

309
00:18:04.892 --> 00:18:08.452
what the assay was designed for. And so in some ways, it's no surprise.

310
00:18:09.012 --> 00:18:12.290
So maybe80% is good enough and

311
00:18:12.460 --> 00:18:16.180
95% is good enough, or 98% to 99% is good enough if it's

312
00:18:16.540 --> 00:18:19.430
amplified. Or is it? So let's compare it to some other

313
00:18:19.440 --> 00:18:22.730
modalities. Here's what we do for lung cancer.

314
00:18:22.780 --> 00:18:26.190
We look at for EGFR mutations, and this was a study from over 10 years ago,

315
00:18:26.760 --> 00:18:30.510
where they looked for EGFR mutations in the same specimen in a number of

316
00:18:30.520 --> 00:18:32.920
different labs. And here's how they agreed.

317
00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:36.470
Here's the number of cases and then their percent agreement on these

318
00:18:36.500 --> 00:18:39.740
cases. So overall, the average reproducibility was

319
00:18:39.960 --> 00:18:43.400
99%. That's what we should offer our patients.

320
00:18:43.880 --> 00:18:47.380
So until we get there with protein, I will still be working on this topic.

321
00:18:48.140 --> 00:18:51.990
I really think that it's possible, and back when we started, back when

322
00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:52.980
Marissa was in the lab,

323
00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.740
it was probably impossible. I'm not sure we had the technology then.

324
00:18:56.780 --> 00:19:00.540
We tried, but we didn't have it standardized, and that was a long time ago.

325
00:19:00.600 --> 00:19:04.440
Now, the computer power has become so strong and so

326
00:19:04.640 --> 00:19:05.160
much more

327
00:19:06.680 --> 00:19:07.600
storage for so little

328
00:19:08.600 --> 00:19:11.780
money that I think we really can be rigorously quantitative.

329
00:19:12.200 --> 00:19:15.720
Although, probably we shouldn't use the standard methods of

330
00:19:15.739 --> 00:19:18.560
immunohistochemistry. We should probably use immunofluorescence.

331
00:19:20.160 --> 00:19:21.900
So how do we measure on a slide?

332
00:19:22.740 --> 00:19:25.680
So we talked about reading. That's pathologist-based scoring, and I told you some

333
00:19:25.700 --> 00:19:29.520
of that. And if you want to measure, you can actually circle the region of interest

334
00:19:29.560 --> 00:19:33.330
and then just measure the intensity of chromagen and sum all the pixels together,

335
00:19:33.380 --> 00:19:36.840
and you can do that. That's a pretty primitive way of measuring, but it does

336
00:19:36.940 --> 00:19:40.440
actually work, and it was one of the earliest ways that people measured

337
00:19:40.900 --> 00:19:44.260
immunohistochemistry. Then there's segment and phenotype and count.

338
00:19:44.380 --> 00:19:48.100
This is what the most common thing is, and this is still what a lot of automatic

339
00:19:48.160 --> 00:19:50.690
software does is that first it segments.

340
00:19:50.760 --> 00:19:54.220
That means it finds all the single cells, and then it phenotypes them with

341
00:19:54.280 --> 00:19:57.940
some biomarker, and then it counts how many are positive and how many are

342
00:19:57.980 --> 00:20:00.800
negative. The problem with this is that in

343
00:20:00.860 --> 00:20:04.640
order to have the software work, you need to have a threshold.

344
00:20:04.680 --> 00:20:08.310
That is, it has to be decided that a cell is either positive or negative,

345
00:20:08.750 --> 00:20:11.260
and then you can count the cells that are positive or count the cells that are

346
00:20:11.300 --> 00:20:13.560
negative. But that's not how biology works.

347
00:20:14.420 --> 00:20:16.180
Biology is continuous information.

348
00:20:16.700 --> 00:20:17.460
And so if you want to

349
00:20:18.440 --> 00:20:21.950
actually get an accurate measurement, I think we'll never get away with

350
00:20:21.980 --> 00:20:25.280
segmenting and counting. I think we're going to have to have some other method,

351
00:20:26.140 --> 00:20:30.000
and that's what we invented all those years ago, which was not

352
00:20:30.060 --> 00:20:33.220
just looking at the segmentation but actually using the area.

353
00:20:33.260 --> 00:20:36.560
This is just an example of segmenting and counting and the flaw with it.

354
00:20:36.660 --> 00:20:40.240
So if your threshold is 15% gray, then you have 50%

355
00:20:40.250 --> 00:20:43.530
positive. But if your threshold was 5% gray, you'd have

356
00:20:43.760 --> 00:20:47.480
70% positive. So which is it? Well, hard to say.

357
00:20:47.520 --> 00:20:51.460
So we invented an H-score so we could combine those things so we'd have

358
00:20:51.480 --> 00:20:54.480
both a score and sort of a pseudo-continuous score.

359
00:20:54.500 --> 00:20:58.460
But in fact, if it was a dark day, that is if your stainer wasn't working a

360
00:20:58.520 --> 00:21:02.080
little bit the same way it did the day before, you might change your score from

361
00:21:02.220 --> 00:21:05.760
145 to 160 with just a 10% change in the

362
00:21:05.780 --> 00:21:09.620
intensity of the stain. So does that happen? Well, actually it does.

363
00:21:09.780 --> 00:21:13.720
This is from David Dobbs and Steve Bogan, who used bead standards

364
00:21:13.760 --> 00:21:15.210
and looked at the limits of detection.

365
00:21:16.240 --> 00:21:20.120
In these assays, this group of dots, each of these dots represents a

366
00:21:20.300 --> 00:21:24.220
CLIA lab. That is a certified lab using a standard

367
00:21:24.600 --> 00:21:27.960
Ventana stainer, Roche stainer, using the actual

368
00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:31.160
instructions in the box. And you can see that there's a threefold

369
00:21:31.240 --> 00:21:34.740
difference in the lowest in one lab compared to that top lab.

370
00:21:35.200 --> 00:21:38.040
And that's just the way it is. It's really hard to fix that.

371
00:21:38.060 --> 00:21:41.860
And Bogan et al. proposed using some sort of standardization

372
00:21:41.920 --> 00:21:45.380
method to fix it. But even though these are auto stainers, there's at least a

373
00:21:45.440 --> 00:21:47.860
factor of three difference from day to day or week to week.

374
00:21:48.300 --> 00:21:52.190
And that makes chromagens not the right reagent for doing quantification.

375
00:21:53.940 --> 00:21:57.870
So, this is just to sort of estimate how right we are or how

376
00:21:57.880 --> 00:22:00.420
wrong we are. And so we had 17 pathologists do

377
00:22:02.720 --> 00:22:05.860
percentage of cells positive, and we calculated the coefficient of

378
00:22:05.880 --> 00:22:09.620
variation. Coefficient of variation tells you your reproducibility and your

379
00:22:09.640 --> 00:22:13.480
precision. And you can see that on average for Trop-2 H

380
00:22:13.500 --> 00:22:17.410
scores with five pathologists, the range of CV was from zero to 75,

381
00:22:17.480 --> 00:22:21.220
depending on the score itself. But the average was

382
00:22:21.360 --> 00:22:21.860
20%.

383
00:22:22.780 --> 00:22:26.740
Shockingly, the average was over 80% for immune cells,

384
00:22:27.720 --> 00:22:31.529
which means that I think that you need to not use an H score

385
00:22:31.720 --> 00:22:35.640
because a coefficient of variation of 80% is not tolerable for

386
00:22:35.680 --> 00:22:39.650
patients. The FDA asks us to get a coefficient of variation

387
00:22:39.680 --> 00:22:41.400
of 10% or less for approvals.

388
00:22:43.220 --> 00:22:45.680
So this is why you shouldn't use chromagens. How many pennies?

389
00:22:48.120 --> 00:22:51.720
How many light bulbs? Well, if we summed up the information of the

390
00:22:51.760 --> 00:22:54.060
intensity of the light bulbs, we could figure that out.

391
00:22:54.420 --> 00:22:57.640
I don't have that done for you. But if we summed up the information of the pennies,

392
00:22:58.080 --> 00:23:01.080
we would come up with five when it's actually 100.

393
00:23:02.060 --> 00:23:05.360
And that's because chromagens don't transmit light. It's physics.

394
00:23:05.420 --> 00:23:07.420
You can't break the laws of physics.

395
00:23:07.440 --> 00:23:11.220
And so I think that this is why I've moved from chromagens

396
00:23:11.240 --> 00:23:14.560
early in my career to fluorescence because you can sum the intensity.

397
00:23:14.940 --> 00:23:18.590
And even when three bulbs are on top of each other, the sum intensity is pretty

398
00:23:18.660 --> 00:23:22.400
much accurate compared to the intensity of looking at how much light is

399
00:23:22.440 --> 00:23:22.820
blocked.

400
00:23:24.400 --> 00:23:26.160
So this is what we invented back in the day.

401
00:23:27.040 --> 00:23:30.260
And I need to mention Bob Camp, who was really pivotal in this

402
00:23:30.300 --> 00:23:33.580
invention that we called AQUA for automated quantitative analysis.

403
00:23:33.660 --> 00:23:35.500
First, we called it Tiresias, but I won't go there.

404
00:23:36.800 --> 00:23:40.220
The concept behind it was to sum the intensity of the

405
00:23:41.200 --> 00:23:45.160
target within a compartment divided by the area, so you

406
00:23:45.200 --> 00:23:46.960
could make something like a concentration.

407
00:23:47.420 --> 00:23:51.170
And so we took a mask, that's where the tumor was, and then we'd sum the intensity,

408
00:23:51.240 --> 00:23:54.910
in this case of estrogen receptor, across that area, and you'd have

409
00:23:55.460 --> 00:23:59.200
ultimately a score initially, but more recently in attomoles per

410
00:23:59.260 --> 00:24:02.560
square millimeter. So how do we get to attomoles per square millimeter?

411
00:24:02.640 --> 00:24:05.900
So it's the same concept, but this is done more recently and just published two

412
00:24:05.960 --> 00:24:08.740
years ago with Jack Robbins, a graduate student in my lab.

413
00:24:09.180 --> 00:24:12.874
And what he didwas figure out how to do immunofluorescence and then

414
00:24:12.924 --> 00:24:16.724
deposit fluorophores, but not just on the tumor of interest and the slide of

415
00:24:16.764 --> 00:24:19.644
interest, but also on a bunch of cell lines.

416
00:24:19.704 --> 00:24:22.844
So these cell lines were produced and then arrayed by our

417
00:24:23.304 --> 00:24:26.724
colleagues. And each of these cell lines was also grown separately and frozen

418
00:24:26.744 --> 00:24:30.404
down so we could determine the attomoles of cell lines per microgram

419
00:24:30.424 --> 00:24:34.324
of total protein. Then we could convert that by figuring out the area

420
00:24:34.344 --> 00:24:38.204
of each cell and calculating the area of each cell so

421
00:24:38.244 --> 00:24:41.824
that for each cell line, we can have an attomoles per square millimeter of

422
00:24:41.864 --> 00:24:45.744
HER2. And while we were at it, we did Trop-2 as well in attomoles per

423
00:24:45.764 --> 00:24:49.273
square millimeter. Then you can, just like in college biochemistry, you can figure

424
00:24:49.344 --> 00:24:53.024
out the intensity of your signal and go back down and figure out your attomoles per

425
00:24:53.084 --> 00:24:56.944
square millimeter. And that's what we've done, and that's how we

426
00:24:57.024 --> 00:24:59.884
can get to absolute quantification of fluorescence

427
00:25:00.904 --> 00:25:04.694
as opposed to quantification of chromagens or immunohistochemistry.

428
00:25:05.304 --> 00:25:08.904
Ultimately, we found out probably we're going to have to use percentiles because

429
00:25:08.924 --> 00:25:12.064
the absolute number of attomoles is not the best way to compare them.

430
00:25:12.084 --> 00:25:15.084
But we'll talk about that a little later on.

431
00:25:15.124 --> 00:25:18.774
This is what this assay we now call the Troplex Assay since it does

432
00:25:18.784 --> 00:25:22.064
Trop-2 and HER2. And this is how it works in the CLIA lab.

433
00:25:22.464 --> 00:25:25.874
When the recuts come to the QDAP lab, that stands for Quantitative Diagnostics and

434
00:25:25.944 --> 00:25:29.644
Anatomic Pathology. And the QIF stainer is

435
00:25:29.664 --> 00:25:33.204
done on a Leica Bond, and there's one control slide, or a CMA, is a control

436
00:25:33.304 --> 00:25:36.264
microarray, for each nine patient slides.

437
00:25:36.284 --> 00:25:39.644
And you can see there's three rows in these Leica Bond stainers. So one per tray.

438
00:25:40.324 --> 00:25:44.244
And then the biopsy is scanned, and the attomoles is calculated for the

439
00:25:44.264 --> 00:25:47.684
entire specimen. Then the

440
00:25:47.784 --> 00:25:50.104
software written by Jack converts the

441
00:25:51.904 --> 00:25:55.604
fluorescent image to an H&amp;E or to what looks like a DAB image or a

442
00:25:55.664 --> 00:25:59.604
chromagenic image. And if you can see, this is what it actually looks like.

443
00:25:59.644 --> 00:26:03.624
This looks pretty much like a DAB chromagen that looks so much like

444
00:26:03.684 --> 00:26:06.924
a chromagen that I can circle the region of interest so we're sure we're not

445
00:26:07.064 --> 00:26:10.884
measuring normal ducts, or we're not measuring stroma down here, and we're only

446
00:26:10.944 --> 00:26:14.624
measuring the concentration of HER2 and Trop-2 in the actual tumor.

447
00:26:14.944 --> 00:26:17.984
Now I showed you this high power because you can see how heterogeneous it is.

448
00:26:18.343 --> 00:26:22.244
And those who want to criticize the fact that this doesn't deal with heterogeneity

449
00:26:22.253 --> 00:26:25.103
are 100% right. But we got to walk before we run.

450
00:26:25.144 --> 00:26:26.944
Someday we'll figure out heterogeneity.

451
00:26:26.964 --> 00:26:30.724
But for now, we average everything within the circle performed by the pathologist.

452
00:26:31.724 --> 00:26:33.994
The result of that looks something like this.

453
00:26:34.064 --> 00:26:37.973
This was 316 cases prospectively collected at Yale

454
00:26:38.004 --> 00:26:39.824
from the Yale Surgical Pathology Suite.

455
00:26:39.864 --> 00:26:43.444
So these are actual breast cancer cases, and they're colored by their actual

456
00:26:43.524 --> 00:26:47.404
IHC score that was given to the patient on the basis of which the patient was given

457
00:26:47.464 --> 00:26:50.644
a drug. If you measure them, you can see we did pretty well.

458
00:26:50.684 --> 00:26:54.294
They got trastuzumab if they were red or orange, and those are mostly up here on

459
00:26:54.324 --> 00:26:58.124
the high end. But down at the low end, where they may or may

460
00:26:58.144 --> 00:27:01.844
not get trastuzumab deruxtecan or in the future, other

461
00:27:01.884 --> 00:27:05.814
HER2 low drugs, you can see that the blues and the greens, the zeros and ones

462
00:27:05.844 --> 00:27:07.664
are essentially interchangeable.

463
00:27:07.684 --> 00:27:11.364
And so that means that we don't have the ability to, by eye,

464
00:27:11.424 --> 00:27:14.994
distinguish low from very low. And in fact, interestingly,

465
00:27:15.704 --> 00:27:19.664
because it's a quantitative assay, we can calculate a limit of detection

466
00:27:19.704 --> 00:27:23.693
and a limit of quantification. And you can see actually that about 5

467
00:27:23.704 --> 00:27:26.884
or 6% of the cases are even below our limit of detection.

468
00:27:26.904 --> 00:27:30.364
Those are probably the true negatives, and those probably patients shouldn't get

469
00:27:30.384 --> 00:27:34.064
T-DXd, whereas all the rest of them might have enough T-DXd to

470
00:27:34.084 --> 00:27:37.774
benefit. LOQ is a limit of quantification, but we don't know what the limit is

471
00:27:37.844 --> 00:27:41.744
yet. And we're working very hard on figuring out what the threshold is for

472
00:27:42.304 --> 00:27:44.544
a response to trastuzumab deruxtecan.

473
00:27:46.104 --> 00:27:50.004
This is also just showing the same thing on a second study where

474
00:27:50.084 --> 00:27:53.564
